{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QXqFEvFTvB82dMr2Ds3XE9","type":"tool_result","content":"60\ttechnique that **shrinks the bytes-per-row** or **shrinks the row\n61\tcount** translates ~linearly to latency.\n62\t\n63\t### 1. Metadata prefiltering\n64\t\n65\t- **Mechanism.** `vec0` (sqlite-vec ≥ 0.1.6) supports auxiliary\n66\t  metadata columns and partition-key columns; KNN can be pre-filtered\n67\t  with `WHERE kind = ?` so distance compute runs only over the\n68\t  matching chunk(s). Cited:\n69\t  [alexgarcia.xyz blog — metadata release](https://alexgarcia.xyz/blog/2024/sqlite-vec-metadata-release/index.html);\n70\t  vec0 features page lists up to 16 metadata columns and 4 partition\n71\t  keys.\n72\t- **Expected gain.** Scales with selectivity. If FathomDB carries 8\n73\t  vector kinds with rough uniformity, prefiltering by `kind` cuts\n74\t  scanned rows ~8× ⇒ ~256 ms. AC-013's fixture seeds a *single*\n75\t  `\"doc\"` kind (`tests/perf_gates.rs:350`), so the benchmark itself\n76\t  gets **no benefit** from `kind` prefiltering. Real workloads do.\n77\t- **Implementation cost.** Schema migration (add metadata + partition\n78\t  cols to `vector_default` or split into per-kind tables);\n79\t  `engine.search()` API extension to accept filter predicates;\n80\t  ingest path change in `_fathomdb_vector_rows` insert\n81\t  (`lib.rs:2846`). Moderate.\n82\t- **Recall / correctness.** Exact within the filter set — semantics\n83\t  change (results restricted), not approximated.\n84\t- **Compatibility.** Plays cleanly with writer lock + projection\n85\t  cursor; vec0 partition keys are chunk-organised so writes scale\n86\t  per partition.\n87\t\n88\t**Verdict on its own: insufficient for AC-013's synthetic\n89\tsingle-kind fixture; valuable for real workloads but not load-bearing\n90\tfor the gate.**\n91\t\n92\t### 2. Partition keys (physical / logical)\n93\t\n94\t- **Mechanism.** Partition-key columns on `vec0` (sqlite-vec\n95\t  feature; max 4) physically chunk storage. Logical alternative:\n96\t  N per-kind `vec0` tables.\n97\t- **Gain.** Same scaling as metadata prefilter; for AC-013's\n98\t  single-kind fixture, zero. For domain workloads with k=8 partitions\n99\t  → ~8× cheaper scans (~250 ms).\n100\t- **Cost.** Either a multi-table search planner (logical) or schema\n101\t  migration (partition_key). Logical option additionally creates a\n102\t  fan-out merge problem at the search layer.\n103\t- **Recall.** Exact within partition set.\n104\t- **Compatibility.** Per-table flavour is incompatible with the\n105\t  current single `vector_default` table assumption baked into\n106\t  `read_search_in_tx`; partition_key flavour is a simpler change.\n107\t\n108\t**Verdict: same as #1 — orthogonal to the gate, but worth shipping\n109\ttogether if we do a vec0 migration anyway.**\n110\t\n111\t### 3. Smaller embeddings (lower dim)\n112\t\n113\t- **Mechanism.** dim 768 → 384 (MiniLM-L6) halves distance compute;\n114\t  → 256 cuts 3×; → 128 cuts 6×.\n115\t- **Gain (alone).** 384 ⇒ ~1024 ms; 128 ⇒ ~340 ms. Neither closes\n116\t  the 25–40× gap by itself.\n117\t- **Cost.** This is **the embedder identity**, not a vec0 setting.\n118\t  `EmbedderIdentity` is profile-pinned via\n119\t  `_fathomdb_embedder_profiles` (`lib.rs:3248-3260`); switching\n120\t  embedders requires a corpus rebuild and a profile rotation. Not a\n121\t  knob we can flip without writer cooperation and a re-embedding\n122\t  pass.\n123\t- **Recall.** Domain-dependent; MTEB shows ~3–6 pp recall drop from\n124\t  768→384 for general-purpose embedders.\n125\t- **Compatibility.** Touches the embedder contract and the schema\n126\t  pinning logic. **HITL Q1: do we have the appetite to switch the\n127\t  reference embedder in 0.7.0?** Default assumption: no.\n128\t\n129\t**Verdict: out of scope for 0.7.0 unless HITL signals otherwise.**\n130\t\n131\t### 4. Binary / int8 quantization (THE LEVER)\n132\t\n133\t- **Mechanism.** Replace the f32 column with `bit[768]` or\n134\t  `int8[768]`. sqlite-vec supports both natively in `vec0`\n135\t  (`bit[N]`, `int8[N]` declarations; cited:\n136\t  [sqlite-vec API reference / DeepWiki](https://deepwiki.com/asg017/sqlite-vec/3-api-reference);\n137\t  [binary quantization guide](https://alexgarcia.xyz/sqlite-vec/guides/binary-quant.html)).\n138\t  Binary distance becomes Hamming (popcount xor) on 96 bytes/row\n139\t  vs 3072 bytes/row of f32 — **32× narrower**, plus 4× lighter\n140\t  arithmetic. Int8 is 4× narrower with SIMD-able dot products.\n141\t- **Gain.** Binary: 32× storage × ~1× arithmetic-density advantage\n142\t  ⇒ 30–50× in practice on memory-bound scans. Published benches\n143\t  (Kyle Howells, Cohere) show 15–40× faster than f32 brute force at\n144\t  ~85–95 % recall@10 with **rerank-on-f32**. Expected p50 if we\n145\t  binarize: **~50–100 ms** for 1 M rows. Int8 alone: 4–8× ⇒\n146\t  ~250–500 ms (borderline on the p99 = 300 ms budget).\n147\t- **Cost.** Schema migration (add `embedding_bin bit[768]` column\n148\t  or a sibling `vector_default_bin` table); ingest path adds a\n149\t  `vec_quantize_binary()` call alongside the f32 insert; query path\n150\t  becomes a two-phase: **bit-distance prefilter → f32 rerank** of\n151\t  the top ~256 candidates. The f32 column is retained for rerank\n152\t  (so storage grows 1.03×, not shrinks). All changes are SQL-level\n153\t  and application-side; no SQLite build flags. sqlite-vec ≥ 0.1.7\n154\t  (our pinned version) already ships the relevant types per\n155\t  [release notes](https://github.com/asg017/sqlite-vec/releases) —\n156\t  no upgrade required to land bit/int8, though upgrading to 0.1.9\n157\t  is low-risk and unlocks the constraint-column KNN refinements.\n158\t- **Recall.** Binary alone: ~70–80 % @ k=10. Binary + f32 rerank\n159\t  on top-K (K = 4–8 × k): ~95–99 % @ k=10, equivalent to brute\n160\t  force for most practical purposes. **HITL Q2: what's the recall\n161\t  floor we'll enforce in the AC-013 RED test?** Suggested: ≥ 90 %\n162\t  recall@10 vs f32 ground truth on the AC-013 fixture.\n163\t- **Compatibility.** Single-writer lock and projection cursor are\n164\t  not affected — both columns commit in the same writer\n165\t  transaction. `VaryingEmbedder` produces normalised f32; binary\n166\t  quantization preserves the sign-mass pattern it encodes, so the\n167\t  fixture remains discriminative.\n168\t\n169\t**Verdict: binary + f32 rerank is the single highest-leverage Tier-1\n170\ttechnique. Plausibly closes the gate alone.**\n171\t\n172\t### 5. Matryoshka / truncated dimensions\n173\t\n174\t- **Mechanism.** Run KNN against a 128-d prefix, rerank on full 768.\n175\t- **Gain.** ~6× on the prefilter pass ⇒ ~340 ms. Less leverage than\n176\t  binary; binary already wins on bandwidth.\n177\t- **Cost.** Requires a Matryoshka-trained embedder (`nomic-embed\n178\t  v1.5`, `text-embedding-3-*`). VaryingEmbedder is not Matryoshka;\n179\t  the AC-013 fixture wouldn't exhibit the recall property."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8d9c2010-470a-469e-a899-a4db3c31910c","uuid":"8f7c77f8-4a10-4ecd-a1b0-6780c6b6ac48","timestamp":"2026-05-27T13:25:05.335Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-20260527T132416Z/dev/notes/0.7.0-vector-cost-research.md","content":"technique that **shrinks the bytes-per-row** or **shrinks the row\ncount** translates ~linearly to latency.\n\n### 1. Metadata prefiltering\n\n- **Mechanism.** `vec0` (sqlite-vec ≥ 0.1.6) supports auxiliary\n  metadata columns and partition-key columns; KNN can be pre-filtered\n  with `WHERE kind = ?` so distance compute runs only over the\n  matching chunk(s). Cited:\n  [alexgarcia.xyz blog — metadata release](https://alexgarcia.xyz/blog/2024/sqlite-vec-metadata-release/index.html);\n  vec0 features page lists up to 16 metadata columns and 4 partition\n  keys.\n- **Expected gain.** Scales with selectivity. If FathomDB carries 8\n  vector kinds with rough uniformity, prefiltering by `kind` cuts\n  scanned rows ~8× ⇒ ~256 ms. AC-013's fixture seeds a *single*\n  `\"doc\"` kind (`tests/perf_gates.rs:350`), so the benchmark itself\n  gets **no benefit** from `kind` prefiltering. Real workloads do.\n- **Implementation cost.** Schema migration (add metadata + partition\n  cols to `vector_default` or split into per-kind tables);\n  `engine.search()` API extension to accept filter predicates;\n  ingest path change in `_fathomdb_vector_rows` insert\n  (`lib.rs:2846`). Moderate.\n- **Recall / correctness.** Exact within the filter set — semantics\n  change (results restricted), not approximated.\n- **Compatibility.** Plays cleanly with writer lock + projection\n  cursor; vec0 partition keys are chunk-organised so writes scale\n  per partition.\n\n**Verdict on its own: insufficient for AC-013's synthetic\nsingle-kind fixture; valuable for real workloads but not load-bearing\nfor the gate.**\n\n### 2. Partition keys (physical / logical)\n\n- **Mechanism.** Partition-key columns on `vec0` (sqlite-vec\n  feature; max 4) physically chunk storage. Logical alternative:\n  N per-kind `vec0` tables.\n- **Gain.** Same scaling as metadata prefilter; for AC-013's\n  single-kind fixture, zero. For domain workloads with k=8 partitions\n  → ~8× cheaper scans (~250 ms).\n- **Cost.** Either a multi-table search planner (logical) or schema\n  migration (partition_key). Logical option additionally creates a\n  fan-out merge problem at the search layer.\n- **Recall.** Exact within partition set.\n- **Compatibility.** Per-table flavour is incompatible with the\n  current single `vector_default` table assumption baked into\n  `read_search_in_tx`; partition_key flavour is a simpler change.\n\n**Verdict: same as #1 — orthogonal to the gate, but worth shipping\ntogether if we do a vec0 migration anyway.**\n\n### 3. Smaller embeddings (lower dim)\n\n- **Mechanism.** dim 768 → 384 (MiniLM-L6) halves distance compute;\n  → 256 cuts 3×; → 128 cuts 6×.\n- **Gain (alone).** 384 ⇒ ~1024 ms; 128 ⇒ ~340 ms. Neither closes\n  the 25–40× gap by itself.\n- **Cost.** This is **the embedder identity**, not a vec0 setting.\n  `EmbedderIdentity` is profile-pinned via\n  `_fathomdb_embedder_profiles` (`lib.rs:3248-3260`); switching\n  embedders requires a corpus rebuild and a profile rotation. Not a\n  knob we can flip without writer cooperation and a re-embedding\n  pass.\n- **Recall.** Domain-dependent; MTEB shows ~3–6 pp recall drop from\n  768→384 for general-purpose embedders.\n- **Compatibility.** Touches the embedder contract and the schema\n  pinning logic. **HITL Q1: do we have the appetite to switch the\n  reference embedder in 0.7.0?** Default assumption: no.\n\n**Verdict: out of scope for 0.7.0 unless HITL signals otherwise.**\n\n### 4. Binary / int8 quantization (THE LEVER)\n\n- **Mechanism.** Replace the f32 column with `bit[768]` or\n  `int8[768]`. sqlite-vec supports both natively in `vec0`\n  (`bit[N]`, `int8[N]` declarations; cited:\n  [sqlite-vec API reference / DeepWiki](https://deepwiki.com/asg017/sqlite-vec/3-api-reference);\n  [binary quantization guide](https://alexgarcia.xyz/sqlite-vec/guides/binary-quant.html)).\n  Binary distance becomes Hamming (popcount xor) on 96 bytes/row\n  vs 3072 bytes/row of f32 — **32× narrower**, plus 4× lighter\n  arithmetic. Int8 is 4× narrower with SIMD-able dot products.\n- **Gain.** Binary: 32× storage × ~1× arithmetic-density advantage\n  ⇒ 30–50× in practice on memory-bound scans. Published benches\n  (Kyle Howells, Cohere) show 15–40× faster than f32 brute force at\n  ~85–95 % recall@10 with **rerank-on-f32**. Expected p50 if we\n  binarize: **~50–100 ms** for 1 M rows. Int8 alone: 4–8× ⇒\n  ~250–500 ms (borderline on the p99 = 300 ms budget).\n- **Cost.** Schema migration (add `embedding_bin bit[768]` column\n  or a sibling `vector_default_bin` table); ingest path adds a\n  `vec_quantize_binary()` call alongside the f32 insert; query path\n  becomes a two-phase: **bit-distance prefilter → f32 rerank** of\n  the top ~256 candidates. The f32 column is retained for rerank\n  (so storage grows 1.03×, not shrinks). All changes are SQL-level\n  and application-side; no SQLite build flags. sqlite-vec ≥ 0.1.7\n  (our pinned version) already ships the relevant types per\n  [release notes](https://github.com/asg017/sqlite-vec/releases) —\n  no upgrade required to land bit/int8, though upgrading to 0.1.9\n  is low-risk and unlocks the constraint-column KNN refinements.\n- **Recall.** Binary alone: ~70–80 % @ k=10. Binary + f32 rerank\n  on top-K (K = 4–8 × k): ~95–99 % @ k=10, equivalent to brute\n  force for most practical purposes. **HITL Q2: what's the recall\n  floor we'll enforce in the AC-013 RED test?** Suggested: ≥ 90 %\n  recall@10 vs f32 ground truth on the AC-013 fixture.\n- **Compatibility.** Single-writer lock and projection cursor are\n  not affected — both columns commit in the same writer\n  transaction. `VaryingEmbedder` produces normalised f32; binary\n  quantization preserves the sign-mass pattern it encodes, so the\n  fixture remains discriminative.\n\n**Verdict: binary + f32 rerank is the single highest-leverage Tier-1\ntechnique. Plausibly closes the gate alone.**\n\n### 5. Matryoshka / truncated dimensions\n\n- **Mechanism.** Run KNN against a 128-d prefix, rerank on full 768.\n- **Gain.** ~6× on the prefilter pass ⇒ ~340 ms. Less leverage than\n  binary; binary already wins on bandwidth.\n- **Cost.** Requires a Matryoshka-trained embedder (`nomic-embed\n  v1.5`, `text-embedding-3-*`). VaryingEmbedder is not Matryoshka;\n  the AC-013 fixture wouldn't exhibit the recall property.","numLines":120,"startLine":60,"totalLines":419}}}
